s 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French name, <i>Olivier</i>, recorded as the name of one of Charlemagne's paladins (retainers), the close companion in arms of Roland in the Chanson de Roland. Whereas Roland is headstrong and rash, Oliver is thoughtful and cautious. Ostensibly this name derives from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i> ‘olive tree’ (  compare  Olive  ), but Charlemagne's other paladins all bear solidly Germanic names, so it is more probably an altered form of a Germanic name, perhaps distantly connected with Old Norse <i>Óleifr</i> ‘ancestral relic’. It has remained in more or less continuous use since the medieval period, becoming ever more popular since the 1980s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":30,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Oliver Shearman was born in 1352, in Yaxley, Suffolk, England, his father, Earl William le Shearman, was 38 and his mother, Alice Le Lacer, was 36. He married Isabella Davis about 1388, in Yaxley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. He died about 1396, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1352–about 1396":"1352–umbes 1396","1352–1396":"1352–1396","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1355–1426":"1355–1426","1396–1487":"1396–1487","1314–1355":"1314–1355","1317–1386":"1317–1386","1352":"1352","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1338":"1338","1426":"1426","1314":"1314","1355":"1355","1487":"1487","1386":"1386","about 1388":"umbes 1388","after 1386":"pärast 1386","about 1396":"umbes 1396","1428":"1428","1317":"1317","England":"England","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, Engla